President Barack Obama and President Truong Tan Sang of Vietnam met at the White House in 2013 to discuss opening a new phase of bilateral relations between the two countries. They decided to form a U.S.-Vietnam Comprehensive Partnership to advance the relationship in areas such as politics, trade, science, education, environment, defense, human rights, and culture. They agreed to increase high-level exchanges and cooperation mechanisms, and to enhance cooperation at regional and international forums. They also reaffirmed their support for peaceful settlement of disputes, the observance of the Declaration of Conduct of Parties in the South China Sea, and the value of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) agreement. The two leaders discussed scientific and technological cooperation, education cooperation, environmental and health issues, war legacy issues, defense and security cooperation, human rights, and cultural exchange. They emphasized the importance of protection and promotion of human rights and the significance of enhancing cooperation in culture, tourism, and sports.